{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"41ad7611-936b-4134-af44-ab5aaae08133","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## 1. `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root, for consistency)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n  </ItemGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**What each property does:**\n- **`EnableMSTestRunner`** — switches from VSTest to the MTP runner (bundled in MSTest ≥ 3.2).\n- **`OutputType Exe`** — required because each test project now hosts its own runner process.\n- **`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`** — lets `dotnet test` discover and run MTP-based projects (needed on .NET 8 SDK; .NET 9+ has this on by default).\n- **`TrxReport` package** — replaces the VSTest `--logger trx` functionality with MTP's built-in TRX extension.\n\n## 2. Per-project `.csproj` changes\n\nNone, assuming the three projects don't already set conflicting `OutputType` values. If any do, remove those so the `Directory.Build.props` value takes effect.\n\n## 3. CI command\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is forwarded to the MTP runner. `--report-trx` activates the TRX extension you added via the package. TRX files are written to each project's `TestResults/` folder by default. To control the output path:\n\n```\ndotnet test -- --report-trx --report-trx-filename <name>.trx\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cf166620-1501-41fe-8342-a6f4da42514b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Project-level changes**: Enable MTP by setting `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` in each project (or better, in a `Directory.Build.props` to keep it consistent).\n\n2. **Since they're on MSTest 3.8.0**, the MSTest runner is already included in the MSTest NuGet packages (starting from 3.2+), so they just need to enable it.\n\n\n3. **For TRX logging**, they'll need to add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package since MTP handles logging differently than the traditional `--logger trx` approach.\n\n4. **CI command changes**: The `dotnet test` command needs adjustment—instead of `--logger trx`, they should use `--report-trx` or the equivalent MTP CLI option to generate test reports.\n\nSince the test projects become executables with `EnableMSTestRunner`, I'd recommend centralizing the configuration in a `Directory.Build.props` file across all three projects for consistency. comes through the `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` package instead, so I need to add the TRX report extension and use the correct argument syntax for MTP rather than VSTest's logger format.\n\nSetting up the configuration files...","outputTokens":1512,"requestId":"A030:3C520:C0E8F5:E119F2:69FE8563"},"id":"6fa904e9-2222-4f79-9614-a62c0f486f6d","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:53:20.603Z","parentId":"c1bc6969-4327-472b-b3cd-17b4e628a06f"}
